Hi, my name is: Mary Beth Nebel

I am a biomedical engineer at the Center for Neurodevelopmental and Imaging Research at Kennedy Krieger Institute and an Assistant Professor in the Department of Neurology at Johns Hopkins University.

How do children learn to interpret sensory information to produce appropriate actions?

I use functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) and video-based assessments of behavior to try to understand this problem. Given the inherent challenges of scanning young populations, I also help develop analysis methods that make the most of the available data by minimizing artifacts and maximizing the reproducibility and generalizability of fMRI-derived connectivity metrics.

Team science is the best science, so if you’d like to collaborate, please reach out!
